    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Okay, that's clearer. So if there is a blockage from something like an insect or ice, how does that actually affect the reading on the airspeed indicator specifically? Does it make the speed look higher or lower than it really is?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the pitot tube is blocked by ice or an insect, the dynamic pressure (the force of the air hitting the front) cannot enter the tube. Instead, the tube only measures the static pressure of the surrounding air. Since the airspeed indicator calculates speed by subtracting static pressure from the measured pressure, a lack of dynamic pressure means the needle will drop to zero or a very low value, making the aircraft appear to be flying much slower than it actually is. This is known as a \"pitot blockage\" error.\n\nHowever, if the blockage is partial or if the tube is damaged in a way that allows some air in but not all, the reading can become erratic, jumping up and down as the plane encounters turbulence. In extreme cases, if the blockage is on the static port instead of the pitot tube, the opposite can happen: the instrument might read a speed higher than reality because the static pressure reference is wrong.\n\nIt is crucial for pilots to recognize this \"ghost\" reading, as flying with a false low airspeed indication can lead to a dangerous stall if the pilot tries to maintain a high speed based on the faulty data. A quick check involves looking for ice buildup or debris, and if found",
